{{Infobox academic | name = Nishitsunoi Masayoshi | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1900|5|22}} | birth_place = {{JPN}}[[Saitama Prefecture]], [[Kitaadachi District]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1971|1|22|1900|5|22}} | death_place = | othername = |main_interests = [[:en:Folklore studies|Folklore studies]] |alma_mater = [[:en:Kokugakuin University|Kokugakuin University]] |workplaces = [[:en:Kokugakuin University|Kokugakuin University]] |degree = Doctor of Literature | URL = | yearsactive = | spouse = | children = }} '''Nishitsunoi Masayoshi''' (西角井 正慶, May 22, 1900 – January 22, 1971) was a Japanese scholar in [[:en:Japanese literature|Japanese literature]], [[:en:Folklore studies|Folklore studies]], and a [[:en:Poet|Poet]] who wrote under the pen name '''Minuma Fuyuo''' (見沼 冬男). He was a student of [[:en:Orikuchi Shinobu|Orikuchi Shinobu]] and was regarded as one of the "Five Scholars of Orikuchi." Nishitsunoi served as a professor at [[:en:Kokugakuin University|Kokugakuin University]] and received a Doctor of Literature degree.
